&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/dameboudicca/"&gt;DameBoudicca&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/dameboudicca/4845710547/" title="Ravensbrück - Two women"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4089/4845710547_4a5dbebee2_m.jpg" width="180" height="240" alt="Ravensbrück - Two women" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;ⓒRebecca Bugge, All Rights Reserved&lt;br /&gt;
Do not use without permission.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
This sculpture, &amp;quot;Two women&amp;quot;, was made Will Lammert and Fritz Cremer and stands on the spot for the crematorium, at &amp;quot;The wall of nations&amp;quot; where the names of all nations which lost citizens at this camp are displayed (you can't see them in this shot because it starts to the right of the figures). &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Ravensbrück concentration camp was specifically for women. 130,000 women entered Ravensbrück, 30-40 000 of them died there - and some were sent on to other camps to died there instead. The nation which by far had most citizens in this camp was Poland. The concentration camp (KZ) of Ravensbrück had its several thousand inhabitants living under dreadful circumstances, working making parts for the V-2 rocket for Siemens, but also textiles and electrical components. It was also a training camp for female SS guards, with more than 4000 passing through. At any one time there was 150 female guards at the camp. For most of the war the camp was 'just' a labour camp (though under gruesome circumstances), but in the autumn of 1944 the SS built an actual gas chamber too. Thousands died there. &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
When the Russian army was closing in on the camp in 1945 the commanders forced most of the women who could stand on their two feet out of the camp and onto the &amp;quot;Death march&amp;quot; - about 20 000 in total. 7000, mostly French and Polish, were handed over to the Swedish and Danish Red cross (The White Buses, with much of the organization of making it possible under the leadership of Folke Bernadotte), and about 3500 women were still in the camp when the Russian Red Army reached it.&lt;/p&gt;

